DataElement.preferredName: Laboratory Procedure Serum Immunoglobulin Heavy Chain Outcome Specify
DataElement.preferredDefinition: the free-text field to specify the result for detection of heavy chains when monoclonal protein is found to be present in blood serum by immunofixation technique.

DataElementConcept.preferredName: Laboratory Procedure Serum Immunoglobulin Heavy Chain Outcome
DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: information related to the results of the medical procedure that involves testing a sample of blood serum, the clear liquid part of the blood that remains after blood cells and clotting proteins have been removed, for immunoglobulin heavy chain, a protein complex that consists of two heavy chains (gamma, alpha, delta, epsilon or mu); the larger of the two immunoglobulin chain types determines the immunoglobulin class (G, A, D, E or M, respectively) and the heavy chain molecules exhibit the same structure and composition, which consists of constant, variable, and hypervariable regions.

ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: A procedure for critical evaluation; a means of determining the presence, quality, or truth of something.

Concepts.definition: Any procedure that involves testing or manipulating a sample of blood, urine, or other body substance in a laboratory setting.

The larger of the two immunoglobulin chain types determines the immunoglobulin class (G, A, D, E or M, respectively). The heavy chain molecules exhibit the same structure and composition, which consists of constant, variable, and hypervariable regions.:Outcome; a phenomenon that follows and is caused by some previous phenomenon.

Concepts.definition: The clear portion of the blood that remains after the removal of the blood cells and the clotting proteins.

A protein complex that consists of two heavy chains (gamma, alpha, delta, epsilon or mu). The larger of the two immunoglobulin chain types determines the immunoglobulin class (G, A, D, E or M, respectively). The heavy chain molecules exhibit the same structure and composition, which consists of constant, variable, and hypervariable regions.
